        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested sensitivity:
We request observations in Band 7 in the most extended configuration with one pointing (FOV=18arcsec) per galaxy. Band 7 comprises multiple chemical diagnostic lines of the ISM and provides the best match in spatial resolution to our HST images, which is sufficient to resolve the gas distribution and kinematics in the cusp at a spatial resolution of 0.13\arcsec (~80pc). Our sensitivity requirement is driven by our primary goal to map the CO distribution and kinematics (at 10km/s) in detail for two LIRGs. 
We have estimated the CO J=3-2 line emission from total CO
J=1-0 line flux observations (Baan et al. 2008: MCG-03-04=120Jy km/s, NGC0695=27.3 Jy km/s)  using an average conversion factor quoted for LIRGs of CO (3-2)/CO(1-0)=4  and linewidths of ~200km/s (Baan et al 2008, Iono et al. 2009, Leech et al. 2010,Wilson et al. 2008). We correct for 50% of extended emission above 2arcsec (Diaz-Santos et al. 2010) and divide the remaining flux by a factor of 100 assuming a mix of diffuse and clumpy gas distribution within 2 arcsec (~1Kpc). The requested sensitivity is 0.7 mJy for NGC0695 and 1.5 mJy for MCG-03-04 at 10km/s spectral binning, which results in signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of at least 15 (MCG-03-04) and 7 (NGC065) in the CO emission line. Given that the emission regions are likely more concentrated, we expect to achieve larger SNRs. Based on the online sensitivity calculator, these sensitivities are reached within integration times of 16mins (MCG-03-04)  and 1h (NGC065).

Imaging requirements:
The FOV of ~18arcsec and the maximum angular scale of 2.5arcsec will cover the spatial sizes of nuclear spiral arms and central concentration (~150pc, 0.3arcsec) and its. We have
verified that we will obtain enough uv-coverage and dynamic range for imaging the nuclear distribution of the dust and gas with the ALMA simulator based on our HST NIR and optical images for the extended ALMA configuration. For both sources we were able to easily reproduce the nuclear morphology using on-source times of 20~mins.

Correlator setup:
One spectral window is centered on the keyline of our study, namely the spectral line transitions of CO (J=3-2) while the other spectral windows cover HCO+ (J=4-3), CH3OH (J=4-3), and SiO (J=8-7) in dual polarizationwith one spectral window (containing the most narrow emission line) designated for dust continuum observation at 880 micro~m. The bandwidth ofthe spectral windows is 1875MHz (1600km/s to fully cover the base of the CO, HCO+ and CH3OH line (including the dust continuum). The central frequency of the SiO spectral window is in some cases shifted to fit into the sideband, but still covers the central emission frequency of SiO
(J=8-7). The channels will be binned in the data reduction process to obtain a spectral resolution of  10~km/s for CO and 50-100~km/s for our secondary lines. The CO emission line will be sufficient for analyzing the kinematic features (rotation, dispersion, outflows) of the CO emission line which is expected to have a
linewidth of ~200km/s (CO 3-2, Wilson et al. 2008).


</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
